---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="The Periodic Table of Weapons is an illustrated catalog of humanity's instruments of war, created by Verge Studios using artwork from the Metropolitan Museum of Art."
>
  <section class="py-20">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-xs font-heading font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-accent mb-6">About the Project</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-heading font-black text-cream mb-10">
        The Periodic Table of Weapons
      </h1>

      <div class="space-y-6 text-cream/70 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          The Periodic Table of Weapons began as a design experiment: could the full sweep of human weaponry be organized into a single, readable format? The answer turned out to be a 36-by-24-inch illustrated poster that catalogs over 50 weapons across five historical epochs, from the first stone tools to modern firearms.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each weapon is depicted using artwork sourced primarily from the public-domain collection of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York. The Met's extensive holdings of arms and armor -- one of the most comprehensive in the world -- provided the visual foundation for the project. Where the Met's collection did not cover a particular weapon, other public-domain sources were used.
        </p>
        <p>
          The poster arranges weapons chronologically within five epochs: the Ancient Age, the Bronze and Iron Ages, the Middle Ages, the Early Modern Age, and the Modern Age. Within each epoch, weapons are grouped by type -- edged, blunt, ranged, siege, and firearms -- creating a grid that reveals patterns in how weapon technology evolved over millennia.
        </p>
        <p>
          The project was originally published in May 2017 by Verge Studios. The poster was sold as a limited physical print run on premium glossy stock. This site serves as the permanent home for the project, offering high-resolution weapon illustrations as desktop wallpapers and preserving the historical narrative that accompanies the poster.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-16 pt-16 border-t border-navy-700/30">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-cream mb-6">Credits and Acknowledgments</h2>
        <div class="space-y-6 text-cream/70 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            <strong class="text-cream">Weapon Illustrations:</strong> Sourced from the public-domain collection of the <a href="https://www.metmuseum.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-light transition-colors">Metropolitan Museum of Art</a>, New York. The Met's Open Access policy makes high-resolution images of public-domain works available for unrestricted use.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-cream">Atomic Explosion Photography:</strong> Public domain image captured by the United States Navy.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-cream">Design and Production:</strong> <a href="https://vergegraphics.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-light transition-colors">Verge Studios</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-16 pt-16 border-t border-navy-700/30">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-cream mb-6">Contact</h2>
        <p class="text-cream/70">
          For inquiries about the poster, licensing, or the project, reach out at
          <a href="mailto:info@vergegraphics.com" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-light transition-colors">info@vergegraphics.com</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
